
Dev Log - 2026-05-09

Summary

Contract hardening day.

Today was mostly about making the worker/control-plane layer more explicit and less implicit. The shape of the system moved from “a set of coded behaviors” toward a governed loop with leases, receipts, validation contracts, and clearer boundaries around what a worker can own at any moment. That mattered because the automation path now has more structural truth: retries are bounded, worktree ownership is durable, and task state can be described without hand-waving.

There was also supporting work around the product surface and release evidence. Persona Studio and the chat/sidebar shell were tightened, the beta handoff and docs evidence were refreshed, and the backend was cleaned up enough to keep the newer control-plane and retrieval work coherent. The day was not about flashy user-facing expansion; it was about removing ambiguity in the runtime and the workflow around it.

What I completed

Automated worker control-plane

Added the campaign spec for the automated worker control plane, including the domain model, task state machine, lease contract, receipt contract, orchestrator policy, API sketch, rollout plan, and task breakdowns.
This gives the work a concrete backbone instead of a vague “agent does work” story.
The new docs make the intended lifecycle legible: branch/worktree ownership, task progression, receipts, and inspection surfaces.
Worktree lease contract and store

Added the lease contract types for worktree ownership and the durable lease store implementation.
Backed the store with database models and a migration so lease state survives process boundaries.
Added tests for the lease contract and storage behavior.
This turns worktree assignment into persistent state instead of an in-memory assumption.
Bounded coding validation

Extended the coding worker to support bounded validation attempts instead of open-ended retries.
Added normalized test result contracts and tightened protocol tokens around validation results.
Updated orchestration and task types so the worker/control-plane path can distinguish successful validation from blocked or exhausted attempts.
This matters because the worker now fails in a controlled way rather than drifting into silent retry behavior.
Persona Studio and shell refinement

Refined Persona Studio persistence and layout contracts.
Tightened the chat and sidebar shell, including diagnostics and interaction surfaces.
Updated tests around shell behavior, persistence, and layout regressions.
This improved the stability of the user-facing frame without changing the product shape.
Beta handoff and docs evidence

Refreshed the weekly current-state override.
Packaged beta handoff and evidence docs.
Kept the release story aligned with current operational truth instead of older assumptions.
This keeps the docs from drifting away from the actual runtime posture.
Backend cleanup and contract alignment

Ran formatter cleanup across backend and test files.
Fixed a duplicate validation error token.
Aligned media/document route contracts and several protocol seams.
This was mostly connective tissue work, but it reduced friction for the newer control-plane and retrieval paths.
Important outcome

The biggest shift is that worker execution is no longer just a set of commands with hope attached. It now has leases, bounded validation, normalized results, and a more explicit task model. That is a real move from informal automation toward governed execution.

The system also became more truthful in smaller ways: protocol tokens were cleaned up, the current-state docs were refreshed, and the UI shell changes stayed inside the existing product frame instead of pretending to be a redesign. The day stopped a few kinds of drift before they became harder to unwind.

