Narrative Log - 2026-05-09

This was a contract day more than a feature day.

The first half of it pushed the automation layer toward something more durable and inspectable. The control-plane campaign spec turned a loose idea into a named structure: tasks, leases, receipts, orchestrator policy, rollout steps, and inspection surfaces. That mattered because the system has been moving toward delegated execution, and delegated execution only stays sane when ownership and progression are explicit. Without that, the automation loop is just activity. With it, the loop starts to become accountable.

From there the lease work followed naturally. A worktree lease is a small thing on paper, but in practice it is one of the places where distributed intent becomes real. By adding the contract types and then the durable store, the work moved from “we intend to own a branch/worktree while a worker is active” to “the system can record and recover that ownership.” That is the kind of state that has to survive process boundaries if the rest of the control plane is going to mean anything.

The coding worker work sat in the same family. The important change was not just retry logic. It was the decision to bound validation and normalize results so the worker can fail in a controlled way instead of wandering through hidden retries or ambiguous exits. That is a small behavioral constraint with a large operational effect. It gives the orchestration layer a cleaner signal and makes the worker easier to reason about when something goes wrong.

The rest of the day kept the surrounding surfaces honest. Persona Studio and the chat/sidebar shell were tightened so the frontend frame stayed stable while the deeper contracts changed underneath it. The backend formatter cleanup and token fix were not glamorous, but they reduced friction in the exact places where contract drift tends to accumulate. The beta handoff docs and current-state refresh mattered for the same reason: the written truth had to stay close to the actual shape of the system.

What changed underneath all of this is simple: the system is becoming less dependent on implicit behavior. More of the important workflow is now named, bounded, or persisted. That makes the automation path safer to extend and safer to debug. It also means future failures are more likely to show up as clear contract breaks instead of vague operational weirdness.

That is what today bought us: less drift, less guesswork, and a control plane that is starting to look like something we can rely on.

